WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.040
Hi everyone, my name is Sean.

00:00:08.040 --> 00:00:12.520
So the goal of my talk today is to basically talk about my journey through getting posit

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:18.100
connect at my firm, because I'm the sole user for connect.

00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:24.559
And so I'd like to start off with an imaginary story where your manager tasks you with running

00:00:24.559 --> 00:00:28.520
an analysis and you have multiple different data sources.

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:31.120
And you know, the BI tools just simply aren't cutting it, right?

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:32.959
And so you have this idea, okay, you know what?

00:00:32.959 --> 00:00:35.799
I'm going to create a shiny dashboard.

00:00:35.799 --> 00:00:41.639
And then you stay up late at night, it's a picture of me staying up late at night.

00:00:41.639 --> 00:00:46.160
I have proprietary data that I know I can't share out publicly, so I can't publish it

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:49.119
to the web via GitHub or things like that.

00:00:49.119 --> 00:00:53.520
So then I decide that, you know what I'm going to do is I'm going to share this to my manager

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:55.680
as a HTML file.

00:00:55.680 --> 00:01:00.799
So that way it's secure, I email it to them, and then they'll open it up in the morning,

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:04.639
and then they're going to be amazed by this fantastic analysis that I have, right?

00:01:04.639 --> 00:01:09.760
But then I get greeted with, thanks for this, but I don't want to download a HTML file.

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:13.279
This simply just doesn't work for me.

00:01:13.279 --> 00:01:19.000
And so, you know, when we're working with data, you know, sometimes the friction is

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
trying to share our work with the stakeholders in our business.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:25.720
And so sharing shouldn't be hard.

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:30.400
And you know, when you deploy things, there's a myriad of things that you need to consider

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:35.160
in terms of making sure that you're not sharing out sensitive information, and then you're

00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:37.639
complying within your IT infrastructure.

00:01:37.639 --> 00:01:43.400
And oftentimes, IT, their job is to kind of keep things secure, but then you want to share

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:48.400
information to your business units, so then everyone's happy.

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:51.879
But then, you know, you're kind of limited in your options, right?

00:01:51.879 --> 00:01:59.239
So fortunately, Posit has an enterprise solution called Posit Connect, and then it's a way

00:01:59.239 --> 00:02:06.040
for you to be able to deploy applications kind of with a one-button click inside your

00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:12.119
ecosystem so that you can kind of share information effectively to your stakeholders.

00:02:12.119 --> 00:02:17.520
However, one of the things that you have to consider is that this is not a free product.

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:22.759
It's an enterprise product you have to pay for, and then you actually need to host it yourself.

00:02:22.759 --> 00:02:26.839
So this is sometimes a limitation in the sense that it's not a software-as-a-service like

00:02:26.839 --> 00:02:31.279
Posit Cloud, where it's fully hosted, you just pay for it, and then you can kind of use it.

00:02:31.279 --> 00:02:36.960
You actually have to pay for it and then implement it yourself on your own servers.

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:41.559
And then at least for me, when I learned about Posit Connect, I typically associated it with

00:02:41.559 --> 00:02:42.880
large teams, right?

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:50.639
And so for me, we have a firm of about 45 people, and I was like, well, maybe this is overkill for us.

00:02:50.639 --> 00:02:54.800
And so today I'd like to share with you the journey that I had in terms of navigating

00:02:54.800 --> 00:03:00.639
and actually ultimately getting Posit Connect and how it's actually impacted my work.

00:03:00.639 --> 00:03:02.600
And so just a little bit about me.

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:04.520
I work at S2G Ventures.

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:09.880
We're a venture capital firm based in Chicago, and we invest in seed, venture, and growth

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:12.720
stage companies, hence the name S2G.

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:17.679
We invest in oceans companies, food and agriculture, and clean energy.

00:03:17.679 --> 00:03:23.720
And I was the first data science hire in 2021, and I'm actually the sole Python R developer

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:24.720
at the firm.

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:28.160
Most of the firm are ex-investment bankers, private equity.

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:29.160
So they love Excel.

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:32.639
This is kind of interesting to chat with them.

00:03:32.639 --> 00:03:34.080
And I'm definitely not a Linux admin.

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:41.520
At least I had pretty rudimentary experience with it, but I'll show you kind of the journey

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:43.600
that I had.

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:47.919
And so the process that I had was about three steps.

00:03:47.919 --> 00:03:52.160
The first one was the trial phase, and then the second one was actually getting an executive

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:57.559
sponsor and having a champion within your organization to kind of get the Posit Connect

00:03:57.559 --> 00:03:58.619
product.

00:03:58.619 --> 00:04:00.559
And the last part was the implementation.

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:05.000
So after you sign the documentation, now you have to actually get everything connected

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.440
and working.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:11.520
And so during the trial phase, what I did was I contacted Posit.

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:17.480
I was asking to get like a 30-day trial of the Posit product that's fully hosted so you

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:19.959
can kind of see if it works for you or not.

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:25.440
And I talked with my manager to get a POC.

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:31.200
And what this is, is I sat down with her, and we were going over like a dashboard that

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:32.200
she would like.

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:34.760
She would want to see the meetings that she has last week, meetings that she has this

00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:39.359
week, and then kind of action items that you can actually interact with and type in

00:04:39.359 --> 00:04:42.920
information and log it back to your Rdata warehouse.

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:46.359
So this is something you couldn't necessarily do with the BI dashboard.

00:04:46.359 --> 00:04:51.160
So then what I did was I was able to use the different applications.

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:57.200
Like I built a shiny dashboard for them, and then we kind of got the buy-in that way.

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:02.440
And so the second step in my journey of getting Posit was actually finding your champion or

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:09.959
the person in the organization that can have the ability to sign on the line for the actual

00:05:09.959 --> 00:05:10.959
contract.

00:05:10.959 --> 00:05:15.880
So find the person that can make the decisions in your organization, and then make sure you

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:22.119
identify what they value and then create that value for them so it's a no-brainer.

00:05:22.119 --> 00:05:26.679
And then the next part is to also identify your non-advocates, because sometimes, inevitably,

00:05:26.679 --> 00:05:30.119
whenever you're trying to introduce a new product in the system, you're going to be

00:05:30.119 --> 00:05:34.760
like, you know, Sean, we already have Power BI or Tableau or whatever, right?

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:40.920
And so you want to alleviate any concerns that they have or reservations with yet another

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:41.920
shiny tool, right?

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:47.399
So you'll be able to show how you can actually provide value.

00:05:47.399 --> 00:05:53.399
And then what I was able to do in terms of my prototype was I leveraged the Blastula

00:05:53.399 --> 00:05:56.859
package to generate programmatic emails.

00:05:56.859 --> 00:06:05.339
And so this is kind of an example here is where you have a report, R Markdown report

00:06:05.339 --> 00:06:11.700
of like a fictitious cookie cutter company where you can send emails of cookie inventory

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:15.179
daily, weekly, hourly, whatever, how often you like.

00:06:15.179 --> 00:06:19.459
And then you can have conditional logic such that if the inventories are high, there's

00:06:19.459 --> 00:06:21.899
no email sent because everything is working fine.

00:06:21.899 --> 00:06:27.019
But then whenever a threshold is met where you have low inventory, you can trigger with

00:06:27.019 --> 00:06:33.540
Posit Connect an email to send out to whoever you want to alert them, hey, something's wrong,

00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:34.540
fix it.

00:06:34.540 --> 00:06:38.820
And so what I did was I took this and I kind of showed the art of the possible within the

00:06:38.820 --> 00:06:40.820
leadership in my organization.

00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:43.100
And this is an example of a Posit Alert.

00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:49.619
So what I did was I created a Markdown report that was able to scan our database to figure

00:06:49.619 --> 00:06:53.220
out if our third-party vendors were tracking our internal emails.

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:56.339
So we didn't want to track them in our data warehouse.

00:06:56.339 --> 00:06:58.660
We only wanted to track third-party emails.

00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:03.660
So us emailing someone else, but not internal S2G to S2G emails.

00:07:03.660 --> 00:07:10.059
And so what this alert did was this alerted my manager and the higher up management that

00:07:10.059 --> 00:07:13.220
this third-party vendor was actually tracking emails.

00:07:13.220 --> 00:07:17.179
And so then it alerted them and allowed them a mechanism to actually act upon this new

00:07:17.179 --> 00:07:18.179
information.

00:07:18.339 --> 00:07:21.140
And so this proved quite valuable to them.

00:07:21.140 --> 00:07:26.739
And then what that ended up doing is it kind of sealed the deal so that the COO was able

00:07:26.739 --> 00:07:28.260
to sign off on it.

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:33.700
And then I was able to outline a plan of action for the first 90 days.

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:37.059
And then it was time to celebrate because it was like, yes, I finally did it.

00:07:37.059 --> 00:07:39.700
It was like a two, three-month process.

00:07:39.700 --> 00:07:41.940
But then that's actually not exactly the case at all.

00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:43.940
You still have to implement it.

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:51.220
And so the implementation was rather tricky because I didn't have a full-fledged data

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:52.220
team with me.

00:07:52.220 --> 00:07:55.820
So as I was kind of figuring everything out, I had to figure out, am I going to create

00:07:55.820 --> 00:07:56.820
a VM?

00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:57.820
How am I going to create the VM?

00:07:57.820 --> 00:07:59.459
Install PositConnect?

00:07:59.459 --> 00:08:06.019
And then make sure the IT consultants were signing off on all the things that I was doing.

00:08:06.019 --> 00:08:08.660
And so it felt like I was in this island of despair.

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:09.859
It's like, literally, it's just me.

00:08:09.859 --> 00:08:12.619
I'm trying to do my stuff, and now I have to spin up this new thing.

00:08:12.820 --> 00:08:16.420
But I actually think of it as like an island of empowerment.

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:20.179
Because when you're kind of solo like that, you can move quickly.

00:08:20.179 --> 00:08:22.140
You can prototype stuff.

00:08:22.140 --> 00:08:24.980
But then you can also iterate quickly as well.

00:08:24.980 --> 00:08:28.500
And then if you make mistakes, you can pivot to try to fix it.

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:36.539
So it is a disadvantage being a solo practitioner, but sometimes it can actually help you out.

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:38.820
But it is a struggle.

00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:40.340
There's no doubt about that.

00:08:40.340 --> 00:08:46.380
And so one of the fortunate things I was able to do was pick cloud platforms.

00:08:46.380 --> 00:08:51.219
Because we didn't have servers on-prem, so I wanted a cloud-first solution.

00:08:51.219 --> 00:08:54.679
And then you have different cloud providers, but I wouldn't get necessarily bogged down

00:08:54.679 --> 00:08:59.299
on the specific ones, like Google Cloud, AWS, or Azure.

00:08:59.299 --> 00:09:01.739
We use G Suite, and we have BigQuery.

00:09:01.739 --> 00:09:04.219
So I was like, OK, let's just use Google Cloud.

00:09:04.219 --> 00:09:06.500
And just pick whatever tool that you like.

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:12.059
And then I try to encourage folks to use cloud providers, if possible.

00:09:12.059 --> 00:09:17.219
Because it's easier to maintain, it's very secure, and then you can kind of pay as you

00:09:17.219 --> 00:09:18.219
go.

00:09:18.219 --> 00:09:19.219
And it's quite simple.

00:09:19.219 --> 00:09:23.460
And I would highly recommend it if I had to do it again.

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:25.820
And then for me, I'm not a Linux admin, right?

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:29.979
So it felt like I was just like, oh, into the belly of the beast with this Linux.

00:09:29.979 --> 00:09:32.739
And so there's no Undo button necessarily.

00:09:32.739 --> 00:09:37.419
So sometimes I've made mistakes where I'm like, wow, I wish I never did that.

00:09:37.419 --> 00:09:41.340
And then you're having to navigate the file system if you're not too familiar with it.

00:09:41.340 --> 00:09:46.260
I was OK, but just handling all these things and resolving dependencies for different Linux

00:09:46.260 --> 00:09:48.960
distributions and things like that.

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:52.580
And then you just basically, for me, I just had to memorize commands.

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:58.619
And after you get used to it after a while, but by no means is it simple.

00:09:58.619 --> 00:10:05.940
And so how I use Connect at work is we have right here is a depiction of our data warehouse.

00:10:05.940 --> 00:10:07.780
And then this represents Posit Connect.

00:10:07.780 --> 00:10:14.340
And so I have R Markdown or Cordo documents that run and take the raw data and transform

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:15.340
it.

00:10:15.340 --> 00:10:17.820
And then I'll actually save this into a pin.

00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:23.460
So I'll have CSV files or RDS files that are saved as model data layers.

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:28.539
So I can have this run every two hours, every day, multiple times a day.

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:33.020
And then I can actually connect this to the FastAPI and host it in Connect.

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:38.140
And then from here, I'm able to deploy Streamlit applications and Shiny applications.

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:45.700
The great thing about Connect is that you can trigger how often something will run.

00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:50.820
And then you can actually control provision or provision access to different applications

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:54.140
so that only the investments team can look at the Streamlit app.

00:10:54.140 --> 00:10:57.500
The marketing team can only look at the Shiny app.

00:10:57.500 --> 00:11:00.820
And it's a fantastic way for you to control all these things.

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:04.260
And because of that, I felt like I can do all these different things just being that

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:05.979
sole developer.

00:11:05.979 --> 00:11:11.859
So I had data pipelines running, automated reporting.

00:11:11.859 --> 00:11:16.039
And you can securely deploy these applications like Shiny, Streamlit.

00:11:16.039 --> 00:11:22.880
And then I also used Cordo to create a website for documentation, technical documentation,

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:25.340
and hosting our intranet.

00:11:25.340 --> 00:11:31.780
To have a landing page for all these Shiny and Streamlit applications.

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:35.099
And some trips for troubleshooting that I had.

00:11:35.099 --> 00:11:39.580
So sometimes, inevitably, when I was using Blastula, things will arise.

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:43.500
So I was using Google or G Suite for our email.

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:49.500
And Google actually no longer supported the less secure apps option to send out emails.

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:53.059
And so I was sleuthing, trying to figure out why isn't this working.

00:11:53.059 --> 00:11:55.960
And so I found out someone had posted an issue.

00:11:55.960 --> 00:12:03.820
And then I was able to find that the Blastula documentation actually had a guide to suggest

00:12:03.820 --> 00:12:05.700
using an app password within Google.

00:12:05.700 --> 00:12:12.200
So if you're ever running into issues, just search on, obviously, Stack Overflow and Google.

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:14.520
But then sometimes, you can look at the GitHub issues.

00:12:14.520 --> 00:12:16.760
And you actually might be able to find the answer there.

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:22.400
So now I just use the app password whenever I'm trying to use Gmail to send out email

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:23.400
alerts.

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:28.119
And some lessons learned that I had was to always create a backup image.

00:12:28.119 --> 00:12:31.679
So whenever I try to increase the cadence, I used to do it once a quarter.

00:12:31.679 --> 00:12:33.940
But now I almost do it once a month.

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:38.000
And then just using Git, as we learned from Colin today.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:42.719
And always document as you go, because your future self will thank you.

00:12:42.719 --> 00:12:48.280
And so this is an actual screenshot from what our VM instance in Google Cloud.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:50.520
So I'm actually running my production.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:54.320
Connect server is a backup, because I want to update Linux.

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:57.200
And I totally, like, Connect just did not work.

00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:58.559
And so I was like, OK, whatever.

00:12:58.559 --> 00:12:59.559
Let's just go back.

00:12:59.559 --> 00:13:02.640
And I thank myself for that.

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:09.239
And so the main takeaway message that I have for everyone is just to try to do a trial,

00:13:09.239 --> 00:13:14.719
see if it works for you, and then identify your executive sponsor within your organization,

00:13:14.719 --> 00:13:16.799
and then kind of implement it.

00:13:16.799 --> 00:13:18.320
And then you're going to have struggles.

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:22.479
But hopefully, I made some mistakes that you don't have to.

00:13:22.479 --> 00:13:26.719
And sometimes your greatest skeptics can be your greatest advocates, right?

00:13:26.719 --> 00:13:31.799
And so I invite the audience to try to collaborate with your different stakeholders, identify

00:13:31.799 --> 00:13:35.799
what their pain points are, and kind of earn their trust.

00:13:35.799 --> 00:13:40.000
And then just continuously deploy things and provide value.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.159
And thank you.

00:13:43.159 --> 00:13:52.119
Thank you so much, John.

00:13:52.119 --> 00:13:53.520
So one question for you.

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:57.359
How hard was it to convince decision makers to buy into Perseid Connect?

00:13:57.359 --> 00:14:04.159
Did Connect provide tools to make that easier, or did you wish they did more?

00:14:04.159 --> 00:14:11.200
I think for me, it was kind of I had to get Connect and kind of show them the value.

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:12.200
It's almost like that.

00:14:12.200 --> 00:14:13.200
What is that mantra?

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:16.599
It's more a beg for forgiveness than asking for permission.

00:14:16.599 --> 00:14:22.479
So I had gotten the trial version of it, and I implemented all these different reports

00:14:22.479 --> 00:14:26.719
and things like that, such that they got really happy and were like, oh, how did you do this?

00:14:26.719 --> 00:14:29.679
And then I was like, oh, I used this thing called Perseid Connect.

00:14:29.679 --> 00:14:32.599
Because you can explain it sometimes, right?

00:14:32.599 --> 00:14:34.320
It's like the show don't tell.

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:40.719
And so I think by creating the value for them, they kind of saw how it was useful.

00:14:40.719 --> 00:14:41.719
Makes sense.

00:14:41.719 --> 00:14:43.320
A very quick question.

00:14:43.320 --> 00:14:45.960
Someone is wondering about the art in your presentation, where you got that from.

00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:49.840
Yeah, so I used Midjourney for all these slides.

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:53.799
And I just did the styling equals zero.

00:14:53.799 --> 00:15:00.440
So for this one, it was like a man walking down a mountain path or something like that.

00:15:00.440 --> 00:15:04.400
And then you say, s equals zero, version five.

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:05.919
So stylization.

00:15:05.919 --> 00:15:10.840
And then I said, in the style of illustrations or something like that.

00:15:10.840 --> 00:15:11.840
OK.

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:12.840
Fantastic.

00:15:12.840 --> 00:15:17.280
And since we have some additional time, there's time to unpack one more question.

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:20.760
Do you prefer R or Python for data science?

00:15:20.760 --> 00:15:25.520
I prefer R personally, like for data wrangling and everything like that.

00:15:25.559 --> 00:15:31.440
A lot of the machine learning stuff I do in Python.

00:15:31.440 --> 00:15:34.320
But I think Streamlit is great.

00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:37.799
I love Joe Chang's comment.

00:15:37.799 --> 00:15:40.719
Streamlit's fantastic until it's not.

00:15:40.719 --> 00:15:44.479
And it's just like the whole, because you have the cache things, right?

00:15:44.479 --> 00:15:50.559
So I'm hoping to port my stuff over to China for Python.

00:15:50.559 --> 00:15:52.679
But I mean, I think I like them both.

00:15:52.799 --> 00:15:58.559
That's the whole nice thing about Connect is that you can use both Python and R, and

00:15:58.559 --> 00:15:59.559
Corda, right?

00:15:59.559 --> 00:16:00.559
Both of them simultaneously.

00:16:00.559 --> 00:16:01.559
Fantastic.

00:16:01.559 --> 00:16:02.559
Thank you so much.

00:16:02.559 --> 00:16:03.559
Thank you.

00:16:03.559 --> 00:16:03.559


